{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_bobwhite_ver01/data/sn96060796/00212476390/1908053001/0301.xml":{"full_text":"THE FIRST NATIONAL BANK OF NOGALES, 22?if?\nUNITED STATES AND SANTA CRUZ COUNTY DEPOSITARY.\nF. D. MIL! FR. Fditor and Prop.\nEntree at SeconJ-Clacs Matter at Ksfilts. Ariiosa.\nJanuary. 18. Is.\nCapital $50,000.00\nSurplus $25,000.00\nr\nOFFICERS: j\nWILLIAM SOU TJOKM ANN, rnmoFXT.\nED. TITCCMB. Vick-Presidest.\nBR ACE Y CURTIS, Cashier.\nOTTO II. HEROLD, Assistant Cashier.\nOfficial Paper of Santa Cruz County\nanil Nocales. Arizona.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES.\nShe gtotflev iflrtte\nOne Ycir\nSix Months\nThree Months.\n2 00\n1 SO\n1 00\nIn Advance.\nMAY 30. 1908.\nNOGALES NEWS ITEMS.\nInteresting Letter From Our Special\nCorrespondent.\nCollector of Customs Cornelius\nO'Keefe has received word of his\nconfirmation by the senate and ha9\nalready filed his official bond and\nexpects to take charge of the office\nabout Monday or Tuesday of next\nweek.\nAll the hotels are having a steady\nrun of trade. Every night new\narrivals 6top over here en route to\nMexico, and the hotels now enjoy\na great part of the trade that for\nmerly went to the Pullman Co.\nThe city park is fast becoming\none of the most delightful places\nto rest in. All day visitors and\nresidents can be seen under the\n.trees' enjoying the shade, and at\nnight it is no uncommon sight for\nparties of ladies and gentlemen to\ncongregate there and enjoy the\ncool atmosphere and listen to the\nband concerts.\nMrs. Steve Bailey lias leased the\nhome of the American Club and\nwill conduct a first class boarding\nhouse there. As such a place is in\ndemand in this town it is needless\nto say the venture will be success\nful. The young men will continue\nto live there though, and enjoy the\ncomforts of a thorough up-to-date\nhome from now on.\nThe members of the town coun\ncil, recently re-elected by the peo\nple, for .another term, were all\nsworn in this week, and continued\nat their work as if nothing had at\nall happened. The work of this\ncouncil has been appreciated by\nevery resident of Nogales, and the\ncompliment just bestowed upon\nthem at the late election is a just\nand deserved one.\nForest Supervisor Willson has\nreceived notification from the de\npartment at Washington, I). C,\nthat the name of the Tumacacori,\nBaboqniveri, and Huachuca Na\ntional Forests will be known after\nJuly first as theCoronado National\nForests, in honor of the great\nSpanish Explorer Coronado, who\nexplored this portion of the coun\ntry in early da3'S.\nThe statement of the First Na\ntional Bank recently issued shows\nit to be in a very fine condition\nfinancially. Having the confidence\nof the government as a depositary\nthe bank is in a position to handle\nfunds of any character whatever\nand guarantee complete protection\nto all who become patrons. The\nmanagement is in safe hands and\nthe service efficient.\nConsiderable activity is notice\nable around the ollice of the Wells\nFargo Express Company, owing to\nthe great amount of business being\ndone there. Large shipments of\nfruit and tomatoes are now coming\nthrough from Mexico consigned to\nSan Francisco parties, which \"be\nsides the usual local trade keeps\na force of employees on the hustle.\nBase ball fever seems to keep up\nand every Sunday the regulation\ngame is played. The boys are\npracticing hard so a3 to be pre\npared to meet the teams from\nGuaymas, Ilermosillo, and Hua\nchuca which are coming here on\nthe fourth of July for the grand\ncelebration that is going to be held\nhere. A series of three daj-s games\nwill be held and some fine playing\nis expected by the visiting teams,\nas well as our own.\nConsiderable activity is being\nexperienced in the business of the\nCustom House all along the line\nfrom Yuma to Douglas. The sub\nports eeem to be vying with each\nother in the amount of business\nbeing done at their respective\nplaces, and the records this month\nare going to be attractive ones.\nNearly eight hundred head of cattle\nhave been imported recently which\nmeans much duly to the govern\nment. The Mounted Inspectors\nare making a splendid record as\nto seizures and as a result of recent\nwork nearly fifty Ziead of horses\nwere seized and sold this week\nwhich also added considerable re\nvenue to this month's receipts.\nThe numerous round ups now\ntaking place are hel ping the mount\ned inspectors in cocuiing horses\nand cattle nut horutoforu sciztd, and\nhence the additional receipts can\nbe expected later on from this\nHourcc.\nOwing to the fact that the weath\ner in this section this spring has\nbeen so cool and pleasant few of\nthe residents have left for the coast\nresorts as has been the role hereto\nfore. The rainy season has not set\nin yet, and as vegetation is some\nwhat backward the prices of staple\ncommodities keep up. In view of\nthis the merchants are doing their\nshare of business anyway, but hope\nfor increased trade which will\ncome when the financial condition\nof the country becomes normal\nagain.\nImmigration officials here report\nan average of eight Mexicans per\nday entering the country. Nine\ndollars per day is the amount the\nhead tax shows up for this month.\nSixteen Chinamen have been ar\nrested, three of whom claim to be\nof native birth, and will soon be\ntried to determine their status.\nThere are no Japanese nor Koreans\ncoming through now. No aliens\nwere passed in transit but three\nChinamen passed through. Twenty-six\nChinamen passed through\nthis port for Mexico during the\npresent month.\nBoard of Trade Meeting.\nThe regular meeting of the Board\nof Trade was held as visual at the\nBoard of Trade rooms Tuesday\nevening with a good attendance of\ndirectors present.\nOne of the matters which came\nbefore the Board' was presented in\na letter from the Geological Survey\nin Washington, stating that the\nGovernment would not be able to\nmaintain longer' the gauging stat\nion on the Santa Crnz River. This\nis an important matter to this\nsection, and it may become- neces\nsarj'. for the Board of Trade to\nagain take charge of the expense\nfor maintenance of such a station.\nAt present the work of gauging has\nbeen discontinued.\nIt is noticeable that the Board\nof Trade is rapidly being placed\nupon the mailing list of all com\nmercial organizations throughout\nthe country, as is shown by the\nfact that no movement of any im\nportance is inaugurated by any of\nthem without this organization re\nceiving an invitation to partici\npate. Just lately the Board has\nreceived two such invitations, one\nfrom the California Promotion\nCommittee, asking the endorse\nment of the Board of a petition to\nthe Secretary of the Navy for a\ngreater armament on the Pacific\nCoast, and another from the or\nganization in St. Louis which is\nendeavoring to hasten the return\nof prosperity. The Board is in re\nceipt of a letter from the Secretary\nof the California Promotion Com\nmittee stating jhat the petition\nlately presented to Secretary Met\ncalf has made a great impression\nupon him, and it is likely that\ngood results will follow.\nThe 4th of July Committee chair\nmen held a meeting immediately\nafter adjournment of the Board,\nand the finance committee was\nable to report a sufficient amount\nalready pledged to the committee\nto enable the plans for a rousing\ncelebration to be carried to success\nful completion. The advertising\ncommittee of the 4th of July cele\nbration is in receipt of a large\nnumber of huge posters to be put\nup in all the towns in this vicinity,\nand as the railroad company has\npromised a one-fare rate from\nGuaymas and all intermediate\nstations, it is likely that Nog a lea\nwill see a huge crowd on the 4th.\nRailroad rates from points north of\nNogales will be announced shortly.\nREDMEN MEET.\nCouncil of Arizona Tribes in Fifth An\nnual Session.\nThe fifth annual convention of\nthe Arizona council of Improved\nOrder of Redmen was held in Tuc\nson last Wednesday, ten tribec be\ning represented from different sec\ntions of the territory.\nJudge C. A. Gildca and District\nAttorney W. A. O'Connor of this\ncity attended the big powwow as\ndelegates from Tribe No. 11, of\nNogales, aud both gentlemen are\nloud in their praise of the roj'al\nreception tendered them by the\nhospital citizens of the ancient and\nhonorable pueblo, one of the oldest\ncities in America.\nDeputy Great Incolionce Leon\ntiodchaux of Doming was present\nduring the session and epoke brief\nlv rvjrH rdin'' the- crowtL of the\norder in Arizona, in behalf of which\nhe has been working.\nThe following officers were chosen\nto serve for the fiscal year:\nJ. J. O'Loughlin of Cochise, Bis\nbee, great sachem.\nA. II. Anderson of Apache, Mor\nenci, great senior sagamore.\nJ. E. Dufton of Pima, Tucson,\ngreat junior sagamore.\nNat E. Hawke of Pima, Tucson,\ngreat chief of records.\nFelix Levy of Tima, great pro\nphet. Richard Sumid of Zuni, Prescott,\ngreat keeper of wampum.\nWiley K. Jones of Clifton, great\nrepresen tati ve.\nThe appointive officers will be\nnamed by the great sachem.\nImportant Fourth of July Notice.\nWe earnestly rovnest all the business\nmen and occupants of private resi\ndences, to placo tboir orders now, for\ntheir decorations on the Fourth of\nJuly. There is very little time left and\nvery often when the purchasing of\nmateria1, for decorations is put off until\nthe last moment, it is imposiblo to Hod\nthe things you need.\nWe expects hundreds of visitors in\noar midst and each one ot use should\nstrive to make our town look most\nbeautiful.\nIf funds permit, the Committee de\nsires to tffer a prize for the best\ndecorated business house, and also for\nthe best residence decorations.\nPlace your order at once.\nCommittee on Decoration.\nNOTICE.\nNotice Is hereby given that the Board\ncf Supervisors will sell at public auotion\nto the highest bidder for cash, on the\nfirst Monday of each month, at 11 o'\nclock A- M. at the front door of the\ncourt house all lireHrms and other\nweapons forfeited to the county under\nparagraph 384 of the Penal Code of\nArizona.\nDone by order of the Board of Super\nvisors. 5 80-4 PXIII. HEROLD, Clerk.\nNOTICE.\nNotice is hereby given that nil pro\nperty holders on Terrace avenue, So\nnoita avenue, west side of Railroad\navenue and West Street south of Craw\nford Street must begiu construction ot\ncement sidewalks in front of their pro\nperties at once. Failure to do so will\nresult in the construction of said side\nwalks by the Street Com mi tee of the\nCouncil and expense for same will be\ncharged to the property holder; as per\nauthority given the Street Commitee\nby the Council of Nogales In regular\nsession September 4th, 1908, and reaf\nfirmed bv a similar meeting of the\nTown Council held on May 11th, ll08.\nBy order of the Council,\nC. M. RATH BUN,\n5 1G 4 Town Clerk.\nNotice to Creditors.\nEstate of Andrew Bartleth, deceased.\nNotice is hereby given by the under\nsigned, executrix of the last will of An\ndrew Bartleth, deceased, to the; credi\ntors of and all persons having claims\nagainst the said deceased, to exhibit\nthem, with the necessary vouchers,\nwithin ten months after the first public\nation of this notice to the said execu\ntrix, at the law office of S. P. Noon, on\nMorley avenue, Noarales, the same be\ning the place for the transaction ot the\nbusiness of said estate, in said County\nof Santa Cruz\nANNA BARTLETH,\nExecutrix of last will of said deceased.\nDated May 12, HWS. 5-16 4\nNotice.\nNotice is hereby given that the Board\nof Supervisors will receive sealed bids\nat their office in the Court House up to\n10 o'caock A. M Monday June 1, 1!M)8,\nfor the care of the indigent sick of\nSanta Crnz C'ountv for the period end\ning February i, 1909.\nAll bids shall specify the. amount\nproposed to be charged for each day\nattendance upon each indigent sick\nperson, including medical attendance,\nmedicine, food, lodging and clothing.\nBy order of the Board of Supervisors\nof Santa Cruz County, Arizona,\n5 25 2 PHIL HEROLD, Clerk\n'Notice of Hearlnl Petition.\nIn the Probate Court of the County of\nSanta Crnz, Territory of Arizona.\nIn the Matter of the Estate of Pedro\nJ. Aguirre, deceased.\nNotice is hereby given that Frank J.\nDuffy has (ilea in this court his peti\ntion praying that the whole of said\nestate he set aside to the widow and\nthat the same will be heard on Monday\nthe firet day of June A. D., 1H08, at 10\no'clock in the forenoon of said day, at\nthe Courtroom of said Court, fn No\ngales County of Santa Cruz Territory\nof Arizona, and all persons interested\nin said estate are notified then and\nthere to appear and show cause, if any\nthey have, why the prayer of said peti\ntioner should not be granted.\nDated May 15th, 1908.\nM. MAHSTELLER,\n5-lft-3t. CLKKIC.\nNOTICE.\nAll accounts due Li B. Fleischer,\nformer owner of the Boston Store, are\nnow duo at Mr. J. a. Faymonville'a of\nfice. The Boston Store, Incorporated,\ndoes not collect accounts due Mr. Fleischer.\nTonkin I Hawkins.\nPractical Mining-,\nContractors and Experts\nAnything in the way of Sink\ning, Drifting, Stoping,\nliaising, Creaking ore\nby the ton, etc.,\npromptly done.\nONLY THE BEST SKILLED\nLABOR EMPLOYED.\nNogales,\nArizona\nGood Meats\nStart the year 1908 by eating meat\nyou know 13 gooa.\nWe have no other.\nCall aud inspect our market and you\nwill be convinced.\nTEETER BROTHERS.\nNogales, Arizona.\nCharles H. Taylor,\nASSAYER\nNOGALES, ARIZONA\nM B. CIIAPA. J. P UURTON\nCHAP A BURTON\nCONTRACTORS AND BUILDERS.\nNogales, Son. Nogales, Ariz\nDARKLLTiS\n''\".yif a nclb convinced\nmmm\n?3lVHHBftC0Fn:E\nI M Lf I NHIIDDPDDFD\nWC 111 Mil, W fcrfST r hlAA\nEH HUR JAPAN TEA!\nENnWBAmPOWKR\nrORSAIXATYOUR GROCER\nn\nWallace, tilore Summerhayes\nConsulting, Mining Engi\nneers and V. S. Mineral\nSurveyors\n.NOGALES, ARIZONA\nS3\nROY TITCOtVJB, MA\n71\nWe offer ore shippers Genuine Calcutta Jute Ore\nBags, -which we import direct from India, at very\nattractive; pric